{
  "blockers": [
    {
      "id": "B-001",
      "section": "API Endpoints — POST /api/tasks/:id/complete, POST /api/tasks/:id/fail; ADR-005 Synthetic terminal runs; Implementation Design — OrchestrationManager.CompleteTask/FailTask",
      "issue": "The new task-level terminal operator path (`CompleteTask`/`FailTask`) is underspecified for the case where a token-fenced active run exists. The spec only says it must \"preserve protected terminal mutation behavior\" — but no such behavior exists today (this is a brand-new endpoint), and the spec gives no rule for what happens when an in-flight worker holds a valid claim_token, is heart-beating, and an operator forces a task-level terminal write. Possible behaviors (reject, force-stop session then write terminal, race with a concurrent `CompleteRunLease`, double terminal write, leak `current_run_id`) are all observably different and all left to interpretation.",
      "rationale": "L-005 (authoritative-primitive exclusivity) and the project's safety posture require terminal mutations to have one authoritative path. A vague \"preserve protected behavior\" clause for a non-existent prior behavior invites two implementations diverging across HTTP, UDS, and contract tests. Without a deterministic rule the cy-create-tasks consumer cannot generate executable tests for the protected path.",
      "suggested_fix": "Add an explicit subsection \"Task-level terminal mutation against an active run\" enumerating: (a) whether `CompleteTask`/`FailTask` rejects when a non-terminal run exists with a held claim_token, or (b) requests `SessionExecutor.RequestTaskStop`+grace+`ForceTaskStop` then writes the terminal transition through the same `task.Service` path that `FailRunLease` uses, including idempotency guard against a concurrent agent `CompleteRunLease`. Specify the precedence order, the actor classification (operator-only vs agent-allowed), and the resulting `current_run_id`/event sequence."
    },
    {
      "id": "B-002",
      "section": "Data Models — `tasks` synthetic terminal runs; ADR-005 transition matrix item 7",
      "issue": "Synthetic-terminal-run creation has no concurrency guard. Two concurrent `CompleteTask` (or `CompleteTask`+`FailTask`) calls against the same never-claimed task can each observe \"no active non-terminal run\" and each insert a synthetic `task_runs` row with the next free attempt number, then race on `tasks.current_run_id` set/clear and on the task-level terminal write. The spec mandates same-transaction set+clear of the projection but does not specify the uniqueness/serialization primitive that prevents the duplicate synthetic row, the duplicate terminal task event, or the attempt-counter race.",
      "rationale": "L-003 requires `task_runs` to be the single authoritative queue; producing two synthetic terminal runs for one operator intent corrupts attempt history and creates two `task.run_summary_recorded` events for one logical close. The grenfield rule does not excuse silent races — it requires the writer authority to serialize.",
      "suggested_fix": "Specify the concurrency contract: synthetic-run creation runs inside `BEGIN IMMEDIATE` with a guard `WHERE NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM task_runs WHERE task_id = ? AND status NOT IN ('completed','failed','canceled'))` and a CAS on `tasks.status` (terminal-target). Also state idempotency: a second synthetic-creation call against an already-terminal task MUST short-circuit and return the existing terminal task/run without writing a second event."
    },
    {
      "id": "B-003",
      "section": "Data Models — `tasks` spawn failure policy item 4 (\"`ClaimNextRun` must not return runs for tasks whose spawn circuit is open\")",
      "issue": "The spec asserts that the authoritative claim primitive must filter out tasks whose `spawn_failure_count >= spawn_failure_limit` (or whose status moved to `blocked`), but provides no SQL/index strategy. Today `ClaimNextRun` is the load-bearing exclusivity primitive (L-003/L-005) backed by `idx_task_runs_pending_claim` (status, lease_until, queued_at, id) which has no task-level columns. Adding a JOIN against `tasks` and a filter on `spawn_failure_count`/`status='blocked'` changes the locking surface, plan shape, and recovery semantics of the most safety-critical query in the system without a design.",
      "rationale": "Authoritative-primitive exclusivity (L-005) means changes to `ClaimNextRun` must be designed up front, not improvised at task time. A wrong index choice can degrade the claim path under load or produce stale reads of `spawn_failure_count` racing with `IncrementSpawnFailure` writes — both of which violate the single-queue invariant.",
      "suggested_fix": "Add an explicit \"ClaimNextRun filter design\" subsection specifying: the exact filter (status check on `tasks` AND/OR `spawn_failure_count >= limit`), the new/updated covering index, the transactional ordering relative to `IncrementSpawnFailure` (does the breaker open atomically with the failure increment, or is it gated by a separate task-status transition?), and contract tests proving (i) a circuit-opened task is not returned, (ii) the breaker reset on successful claim is durable in the same transaction."
    },
    {
      "id": "B-004",
      "section": "Implementation Design — Notification cursor primitive; ADR-003 Open Questions; Extensibility section (\"No bridge SDK wire change is required unless bridge delivery consumers need cursor status exposure\")",
      "issue": "`internal/notifications` ships a brand-new shared primitive (table, migration, CursorStore, hooks, observe events, four invariants) but the techspec does not migrate a single existing consumer to use it. Bridge delivery, thread notifier, and SSE replay are all named as future tenants but no MVP consumer is enumerated. The result is a half-finished surface: schema + API + tests + docs land with zero production callers, which is exactly the partial-surface completion the architecture rules forbid.",
      "rationale": "CLAUDE.md \"No partial-surface completions\" + L-006 (greenfield delete-not-adapt). A primitive without a consumer cannot prove monotonic-advance / at-least-once / idempotent-replay invariants under realistic load and ships dead code into a greenfield-alpha tree. ADR-003's own \"Risks\" section calls out exactly this failure mode.",
      "suggested_fix": "Either (a) name at least one MVP consumer migration in the same TechSpec — e.g., `internal/bridges` thread/per notifier moves its existing per-route advancement onto `CursorStore` with the cursor state replacing `bridge_routes.last_activity_at`-style ad hoc tracking — and add a fresh-DB+reopen integration test for that consumer, or (b) defer the entire `internal/notifications` package to a follow-up TechSpec that lands the consumer alongside the primitive. Do not ship a primitive without a real caller."
    },
    {
      "id": "B-005",
      "section": "Implementation Design — Core Interfaces (OrchestrationManager.IncrementSpawnFailure / ResetSpawnFailure); Spawn failure policy item 5 (\"Scheduler/session code observes spawn outcomes and calls task-service methods\")",
      "issue": "The spec says \"task-service-owned counter; scheduler/session code observes spawn outcomes and calls task-service methods\" without specifying which package observes which spawn outcome, what the failure-classification source of truth is (mapping arbitrary spawn errors to `spawn_failed` / `session_unreachable` / `provider_auth`), or where the `Reset` hook fires (\"first successful claim/session attachment\" — but claim and session attachment are distinct events with different actors). This is the safety-critical integration point that decides whether the breaker fires correctly.",
      "rationale": "L-005 requires the call-site that owns the transition to dispatch hooks — but the techspec must name that call-site. \"Scheduler/session code\" is not a call-site; it is two different packages with different lifetimes and concurrency guarantees. Ambiguity here will surface as flapping breakers, lost increments, or breakers that never reset.",
      "suggested_fix": "Specify exactly one observer per outcome class: e.g., `internal/session.Manager` (or cordinator runtime) is the source of truth for spawn classification, calls `task.Service.IncrementSpawnFailure(ctx, SpawnFailure{Reason: ...})` synchronously after spawn-failure classification, and calls `task.Service.ResetSpawnFailure(ctx, SpawnFailureReset{...})` from the `AttachRunSession` path (or the first successful `StartRun`). State precisely which one resets and why claim does not (claim alone may still spawn-fail). Add an integration test for the full flap-then-recover sequence."
    },
    {
      "id": "B-006",
      "section": "Implementation Design — Core Interfaces (OrchestrationManager.MaintainCurrentRunID); ADR-005 invariant",
      "issue": "`MaintainCurrentRunID(ctx, mutation, actor)` is exposed as a first-class method on the orchestration interface, with set/clear actions and an `ExpectedRunID` field. Even with the rule \"only task-service-owned transition methods may call it\", placing it on a public interface contract is the exact misuse-vector ADR-005 warns against — any future caller (including coordinator, scheduler, extension) can call `MaintainCurrentRunID` and accidentally treat the projection as authority.",
      "rationale": "ADR-005 is explicit: `current_run_id` is a read projection, never authority. Public surface area for projection mutation is indistinguishable from authority surface area; the invariant is then enforced only by review discipline, which lessons (L-005, L-012) say is insufficient.",
      "suggested_fix": "Remove `MaintainCurrentRunID` from the OrchestrationManager interface. Make set/clear unexported helpers callable only from inside the existing transition methods (`ClaimNextRun`, `StartRun`, `AttachRunSession`, `CompleteRunLease`, `FailRunLease`, `ReleaseRunLease`, `ReleaseSessionRunLeases`, `RecoverExpiredRunLeases`, synthetic-terminal creation, cancel/archive/delete). Add a boundary test in `internal/task` that fails if the helper is referenced from any non-task-service file."
    },
    {
      "id": "B-007",
      "section": "API Endpoints — POST /api/tasks/:id/complete, POST /api/tasks/:id/fail; CLI, Tools, and Agent Surfaces",
      "issue": "Authorization for the new task-level terminal endpoints is not specified. The spec says agent paths (`POST /api/agent/tasks/:run_id/complete`) resolve through session-bound lookup, but the new task-level operator path (`/api/tasks/:id/complete`) is not labeled operator-only versus agent-allowed. Any agent able to hit `/api/tasks/:id/complete` could close a task it doesn't own — bypassing claim_token / lease semantics that protect the run-level path.",
      "rationale": "Repo-rule: agent-manageable-by-default + claim_token-secrecy + session-bound lease lookup. If the operator task-level endpoint is also reachable from agent UDS without explicit authorization rules, it becomes a backdoor around claim-token enforcement (L-005). The same applies to `task_complete-task` CLI verb (which side mounts that?).",
      "suggested_fix": "State explicitly that `POST /api/tasks/:id/complete` and `/fail` are operator-only paths (HTTP + operator UDS), not exposed under `/agent/*` or in the autonomy toolset; document the authorization boundary in the techspec, the OpenAPI spec, and the CLI verb description; add a contract test that a session-actor calling the task-level path receives the foreign-mutation error."
    }
  ],
  "nits": [
    {
      "id": "N-001",
      "section": "Implementation Design — OrchestrationManager interface",
      "issue": "Treating `OrchestrationManager` as a separate interface alongside the existing `task.Manager` invites two consumers wiring the same underlying `task.Service` twice.",
      "suggested_fix": "Either fold these methods directly into the existing `task.Manager`, or state explicitly that `OrchestrationManager` is a logical decomposition implemented by `task.Service` and consumed only by named callers (cordinator runtime, scheduler health sink) — and that no new struct/wiring is added at composition root."
    },
    {
      "id": "N-002",
      "section": "Cursor advancement invariants — \"unless the payload is an idempotent replay of the same confirmed delivery metadata\"",
      "issue": "Idempotent replay equivalence is undefined.",
      "suggested_fix": "Specify the replay key explicitly: `Advance` accepts a non-strictly-increasing `last_sequence` if and only if `delivery_id` matches the stored `last_delivery_id` for that cursor row; otherwise return `ErrNonMonotonicCursor`. Add `last_delivery_id` to the `notification_cursors` schema."
    },
    {
      "id": "N-003",
      "section": "Hook dispatch mapping — `scheduler.bad_tick_detected`, `scheduler.bad_tick_cooldown_started`",
      "issue": "Dispatch column says \"`internal/scheduler` through read-only health telemetry\" but doesn't disambiguate whether these are typed `internal/observe` events or `internal/hooks` taxonomy entries.",
      "suggested_fix": "State explicitly that scheduler-side observability is `internal/observe` typed events only; no `scheduler.*` hook taxonomy is introduced (consistent with L-005 anti-pattern guidance)."
    },
    {
      "id": "N-004",
      "section": "Test Strategy — HTTP/UDS parity",
      "issue": "Required Action lists \"Add parity tests for HTTP/UDS\" but the test plan does not enumerate which endpoints get parity tests.",
      "suggested_fix": "List the parity-test matrix explicitly: every new/modified endpoint (`/api/tasks/:id/complete|fail`, `/api/task-runs/:id/complete|fail`, `/api/agent/tasks/:run_id/complete|fail`, `/api/agent/context`, `/api/tasks/dashboard`) requires an HTTP-vs-UDS shape+behavior test."
    },
    {
      "id": "N-005",
      "section": "CLI, Tools, and Agent Surfaces — `agh task complete-task` / `agh task fail-task`",
      "issue": "Hyphenated verbs are uncommon for cobra subcommands and risk drifting from existing `agh task complete <run-id>` mental model.",
      "suggested_fix": "Consider `agh task close --status=completed|failed <task-id>` or a `task-level` subgroup; if the hyphenated form stays, ship help text + docs alignment in the same PR."
